CALCULATOR SYSTEM
System Description

The Calculator System is a software application designed to perform basic mathematical operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. The system allows users to input numbers and instantly receive accurate results. It provides a simple and user-friendly interface that can be used by students, teachers, employees, and other users who need quick mathematical computations.

This system helps improve efficiency and accuracy in solving mathematical problems compared to manual calculations.

Software Development Methodology

The system will use the Agile development methodology. Agile divides the development process into small phases called sprints, where features are developed, tested, and improved continuously.

Agile Process
Planning – Identify system requirements and calculator features.
Design – Create the calculator interface and system structure.
Development – Build the calculator functions and operations.
Testing – Test the system to detect errors or incorrect calculations.
Deployment – Release the calculator system for users.
Feedback and Improvement – Improve the system based on user feedback.

Agile helps the development team quickly adapt to changes and continuously improve the system.

Design Patterns Used
1. Model–View–Controller (MVC)

The MVC design pattern separates the system into three parts:

Model – Manages the mathematical operations and data.
View – Displays the calculator interface and results.
Controller – Handles user input and system processing.

This improves the system’s organization, maintainability, and scalability.

2. Singleton Pattern

The Singleton pattern ensures that only one instance of the calculator engine exists in the system. This helps manage resources efficiently.

3. Factory Pattern

The Factory pattern is used to create different mathematical operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division without directly specifying the exact operation class.

DevOps Principles Applied

DevOps practices will be used to improve the development and deployment process.

Version Control – Git will track changes in the code.
Continuous Integration (CI) – Automatically test code when updates are made.
Continuous Deployment (CD) – Automatically deploy system updates.
Monitoring – Track system performance and detect issues.
Real-World Problem Addressed

Many people need fast and accurate calculations for school, work, and daily activities. Manual computation may take time and can lead to errors. This system solves that problem by providing a quick, reliable, and easy-to-use calculator application for everyday mathematical computations.